{"findings":[{"problem":"Unconditional dereference in `alloc_tag_set_inaccurate()` causes a kernel panic for `_noprof` early allocations.","severity":"Critical","severity_explanation":"In `__pgalloc_tag_add`, if `page_ext` is not available, the code executes `alloc_tag_set_inaccurate(current->alloc_tag)`. However, `current->alloc_tag` is `NULL` outside of `alloc_hooks()` macro blocks. Early boot allocations often use `_noprof` variants (e.g., `kmemleak_alloc` falling back to buddy allocator, as noted in the commit message). Since `alloc_tag_set_inaccurate(struct alloc_tag *tag)` performs a blind bitwise OR (`tag->ct.flags |= CODETAG_FLAG_INACCURATE`) without checking if `tag` is `NULL`, this will predictably cause a NULL pointer dereference and crash the system during boot."},{"problem":"Use-After-Free and Execution-After-Free due to lack of synchronization around `__initdata` and `__init` memory.","severity":"Critical","severity_explanation":"The variables `early_pfns` and `alloc_tag_add_early_pfn_ptr` are marked as `__initdata` and `__init` data respectively. Since `__alloc_tag_add_early_pfn` is lockless and called with preemption enabled, a secondary CPU executing it can be preempted or delayed (e.g. via interrupts) between reserving the array index (or checking the function pointer) and writing the PFN (or calling the pointer). If the boot process completes and calls `free_initmem()`, the delayed thread will resume and write its PFN into active kernel memory that has overwritten the array, causing an arbitrary UAF write. Similarly, it may jump to a freed function address."},{"problem":"Data race in lockless array insertion causes missed early PFNs and corrupted accounting for PFN 0.","severity":"High","severity_explanation":"In systems with `CONFIG_DEFERRED_STRUCT_PAGE_INIT`, `clear_early_alloc_pfn_tag_refs` can run concurrently with allocations on secondary CPUs. `__alloc_tag_add_early_pfn` increments `early_pfn_count` via `atomic_try_cmpxchg` before writing the PFN. The cleanup reader loop will iterate up to the incremented count and read `early_pfns[old_idx]` before the concurrent thread has written to it. This results in the reader seeing `0` (uninitialized memory), erroneously clearing the tag for PFN 0, and permanently missing the actual early allocation. Allocations arriving slightly later, before `alloc_tag_add_early_pfn_ptr` is nullified, will also be silently discarded."},{"problem":"Incomplete tracking for high-order allocations triggers false warnings if pages are later split.","severity":"High","severity_explanation":"When an early high-order allocation (where `nr > 1`) occurs, `__pgalloc_tag_add` only logs the base PFN (`page_to_pfn(page)`) in the tracking array. If this early allocation is later split (e.g., via `split_page()`), `pgalloc_tag_split()` will return without modifying the tail pages' tags because `__pgalloc_tag_get()` returns `NULL` prior to `page_ext` initialization. Later, the cleanup loop sets `CODETAG_EMPTY` only on the base PFN. When the tail pages are eventually freed, their uninitialized `page_ext` references will falsely trigger the `alloc_tag was not set` warning."},{"problem":"Hardcoded `EARLY_ALLOC_PFN_MAX` limit leaves the original bug in place for large configurations.","severity":"High","severity_explanation":"The array size is fixed at 8192. Systems with large core counts, NUMA topologies, or heavy early SLAB fallbacks to the buddy allocator can easily exceed this limit. When the array overflows, the tracking silently stops. When these untracked pages are later freed, their uninitialized `page_ext` codetags will trigger the exact `alloc_tag was not set` warning this patch was designed to fix."},{"problem":"Spurious warnings will still occur for early-allocated pages freed during the `page_ext_init` window.","severity":"High","severity_explanation":"`page_ext_init()` initializes memory sections sequentially, allowing `get_page_tag_ref()` to return true for populated sections immediately. However, `clear_early_alloc_pfn_tag_refs()` is only invoked at the very end of this process via `invoke_init_callbacks()`. If an early-allocated page belonging to an already-populated section is freed during this iteration window, `__pgalloc_tag_sub` will retrieve a valid `page_ext` reference but find its codetag still `NULL`, falsely triggering the `alloc_tag was not set` warning."}],"fixes":"","review_inline":"commit 67c340de4d02daf782e2e9069b7cf9b83a3df927
Author: Hao Ge <hao.ge@linux.dev>

mm/alloc_tag: clear codetag for pages allocated before page_ext initialization

This patch tracks early page allocations made before page_ext is initialized
by storing their PFNs in a fixed-size array. Once page_ext initialization
completes, the tracked pages have their codetags cleared to prevent warnings
when they are subsequently freed.

> diff --git a/lib/alloc_tag.c b/lib/alloc_tag.c
> index 58991ab09d84b..7b1812768af9a 100644
> --- a/lib/alloc_tag.c
> +++ b/lib/alloc_tag.c

[ ... ]

> +#define EARLY_ALLOC_PFN_MAX		8192
> +
> +static unsigned long early_pfns[EARLY_ALLOC_PFN_MAX] __initdata;
> +static atomic_t early_pfn_count __initdata = ATOMIC_INIT(0);

Is it safe to use a hardcoded limit of 8192 here? On systems with large core
counts or NUMA topologies, early SLAB fallbacks to the buddy allocator might
exceed this limit, causing the untracked pages to trigger the original
warning when freed.

Also, since these are marked __initdata, could a secondary CPU executing an
early allocation be delayed (e.g., by an interrupt) and write to early_pfns
after free_initmem() has already freed it, causing a use-after-free?

> +static void __init __alloc_tag_add_early_pfn(unsigned long pfn)
> +{
> +	int old_idx, new_idx;
> +
> +	do {
> +		old_idx = atomic_read(&early_pfn_count);
> +		if (old_idx >= EARLY_ALLOC_PFN_MAX) {
> +			pr_warn_once("Early page allocations before page_ext init exceeded EARLY_ALLOC_PFN_MAX (%d)\n",
> +				      EARLY_ALLOC_PFN_MAX);
> +			return;
> +		}
> +		new_idx = old_idx + 1;
> +	} while (!atomic_try_cmpxchg(&early_pfn_count, &old_idx, new_idx));
> +
> +	early_pfns[old_idx] = pfn;
> +}

Could this lockless array insertion race with clear_early_alloc_pfn_tag_refs?

The count is incremented via atomic_try_cmpxchg before the PFN is actually
written to early_pfns[old_idx]. If the cleanup loop reads early_pfn_count
right after the increment but before the write completes, it might read
uninitialized memory (or 0), missing the actual allocation entirely.

> +static void (*alloc_tag_add_early_pfn_ptr)(unsigned long pfn) __refdata =
> +		__alloc_tag_add_early_pfn;

Similarly, __alloc_tag_add_early_pfn is an __init function. If a delayed
thread tries to call this pointer after boot completes, could it jump to
freed memory?

> +static void __init clear_early_alloc_pfn_tag_refs(void)
> +{
> +	unsigned int i;
> +
> +	for (i = 0; i < atomic_read(&early_pfn_count); i++) {
> +		unsigned long pfn = early_pfns[i];

The page_ext_init function initializes memory sections sequentially. If an
early-allocated page from a newly initialized section is freed before
clear_early_alloc_pfn_tag_refs runs at the end of the init callbacks,
__pgalloc_tag_sub will get a valid page_ext reference but find a NULL
codetag.

Will this still trigger the exact "alloc_tag was not set" warning this patch
intends to fix?

> diff --git a/mm/page_alloc.c b/mm/page_alloc.c
> index 192f7cbbe01d9..a35e715adde98 100644
> --- a/mm/page_alloc.c
> +++ b/mm/page_alloc.c

[ ... ]

> @@ -1257,6 +1257,13 @@ void __pgalloc_tag_add(struct page *page, struct task_struct *task,
>  		alloc_tag_add(&ref, task->alloc_tag, PAGE_SIZE * nr);
>  		update_page_tag_ref(handle, &ref);
>  		put_page_tag_ref(handle);
> +	} else {
> +		/*
> +		 * page_ext is not available yet, record the pfn so we can
> +		 * clear the tag ref later when page_ext is initialized.
> +		 */
> +		alloc_tag_add_early_pfn(page_to_pfn(page));

If nr > 1 (a high-order allocation), we only record the base PFN here.
If this allocation is later split before the tags are cleared, the tail
pages will not have their codetags updated. When those tail pages are later
freed, will they trigger the "alloc_tag was not set" warning?

> +		alloc_tag_set_inaccurate(current->alloc_tag);
>  	}
>  }

Is it safe to pass current->alloc_tag directly to alloc_tag_set_inaccurate
here?

For early boot allocations that use _noprof variants (such as kmemleak_alloc
falling back to the buddy allocator), current->alloc_tag is NULL outside of
alloc_hooks macro blocks.

Since alloc_tag_set_inaccurate unconditionally dereferences the tag to set a
flag, won't this cause a NULL pointer dereference panic during boot?

